\description{
The Discrete Beta (DBT) distribution models ordinal rating data on a fixed
integer scale \eqn{R \in \{1, \dots, k\}} by discretizing an underlying
continuous Beta distribution at \eqn{k - 1} evenly-spaced thresholds
\eqn{\gamma_j = j / k}. Unlike proportional-odds style models, which fix
the underlying distribution and estimate the thresholds, the Discrete Beta
fixes the thresholds and estimates the two shape parameters of the
underlying Beta distribution instead. This keeps the model parsimonious
(only 2 parameters) while remaining flexible enough to reproduce "U" and "J"
(non-monotonic convex) shapes that are common in rating data and that
proportional-odds models cannot capture (Sciandra et al., 2024).
}
\details{
Writing \eqn{\alpha = \mu \phi} and \eqn{\beta = (1 - \mu)\phi} for the
shape parameters of the underlying Beta distribution, the probability mass
function is (Sciandra et al., 2024, eq. 2)
\deqn{P(R = j) = F_B(j/k; \alpha, \beta) - F_B((j-1)/k; \alpha, \beta), \quad j = 1, \dots, k}
where \eqn{F_B} is the Beta CDF.

\code{rbetadiscrete()} uses the equivalent, faster generative representation:
draw a continuous \eqn{X \sim Beta(\alpha, \beta)} and set
\eqn{R = \lceil k X \rceil}, clipped to \verb{[1, k]}.

When \code{pzero > 0}, a hurdle is added at 0: with probability \code{pzero} the
response is 0, and with probability \code{1 - pzero} it is generated from the
Discrete Beta distribution described above, i.e.
\deqn{P(R = 0) = \code{pzero}, \quad P(R = j) = (1 - \code{pzero}) \times [F_B(j/k) - F_B((j-1)/k)], \quad j = 1, \dots, k}

\strong{Special cases:}
\itemize{
\item \code{mu = 0.5}, \code{phi = 1} (i.e. \code{alpha = beta = 1}): reduces to the discrete
Uniform distribution on \code{1:k}.
\item \verb{alpha, beta < 1}: "U"/"J"-shaped, with mass concentrated in the tails.
\item \verb{alpha, beta > 1}: concave, with mass concentrated around the middle
category.
\item \code{phi -> Inf} (with \code{mu} fixed): mass concentrates on a single category.
\item \code{pzero = 0}: reduces to the pure Discrete Beta model (no hurdle).
}

Note that \code{y = 0} is always handled by \code{pzero} alone, and \code{k} always refers to the
number of categories of the \emph{non-zero} \code{1:k} part of the scale. What
\emph{does} require some care is deciding what \code{k} should be and whether to
estimate or fix \code{pzero}, depending on how the zero in your data arose:
\itemize{
\item Scale is \code{0:N} and 0 is \emph{not} a hurdle (just the lowest of \code{N + 1}
ordinary ordinal categories, e.g., a 0-10 rating scale with no excess of
zeros): recode the data to \code{1:(N + 1)} (add 1 to every response), use
\code{vint(N + 1)}, and fix \code{pzero = 0} as shown below.
\item Scale is \code{0:N} and 0 \emph{is} a hurdle (e.g., a mix of a genuine/excess "zero"
response with an ordinal \code{1:N} scale): keep the data as-is, use \code{vint(N)}
(i.e., the total number of categories \emph{minus} the hurdle category), and
let \code{pzero} be estimated (optionally with predictors, \code{pzero ~ x}).
\item Scale is \code{1:N} with excess responses piling up at the low end (e.g., a
floor effect at the lowest category): recode by subtracting 1
(\code{1:N} becomes \code{0:(N - 1)}), then proceed as in the previous bullet,
i.e., \code{vint(N - 1)} and estimate \code{pzero}.
}
}
